    <font size="2"> <i>February 19, 2002---Energy traders are working hard to shore up investor confidence in the wake of Enron. Suffering from what is rapidly becoming known as the “Enron effect” Mirant has lost 60 per cent of its shareholder value. "We were suddenly and unexpectedly downgraded from a BBB flat credit rating to a BB+ by Moody&#39;s," said Marce Fuller, Mirant president and chief executive.</i><br>
    <br>
    "Today we&#39;re facing capital markets that are effectively closed to our company." Ms Fuller used her company as a proxy last week to explain to the annual Cambridge Energy Research Associates conference how Enron&#39;s rapid demise had undermined the confidence of the public, investors and politicians... <a href="http://www.eyeforenergy.com/content.asp?nli=energy&nld=2/21/2002&news=25928"> 
